## 1. Copy the bundle into `public/`

**bash**

```bash
cp dist/widget.js public/widget.js
cp dist/widget.css public/widget.css
```

**PowerShell**

```powershell
Copy-Item dist/widget.js public/widget.js
Copy-Item dist/widget.css public/widget.css
```

> Build-time-frozen frontend containers need a **rebuild** before the
> new assets take effect — copying files into a running container is a
> no-op.

## 2. Load the widget from your root layout

`app/layout.tsx`:

```tsx
import Script from "next/script";

export default function RootLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <html lang="{{locale}}">
      <body>
        {children}
        <link rel="stylesheet" href="/widget.css" />
        <Script
          src="/widget.js"
          strategy="afterInteractive"
          data-backend-url="{{atwBackendOrigin}}"
          data-api-base-url="{{hostApiOrigin}}"
          data-auth-mode="{{authMode}}"
{{#if authTokenKey}}          data-auth-token-key="{{authTokenKey}}"
{{/if}}          data-launcher-position="bottom-right"
          data-locale="{{locale}}"
{{#if loginUrl}}          data-login-url="{{loginUrl}}"
{{/if}}        />
      </body>
    </html>
  );
}
```

The widget reads its tool catalogue at boot from
`{{atwBackendOrigin}}/tools` — there is no `data-allowed-tools`
attribute (FR-015).

## 3. CORS configuration on your host API

Your host API at `{{hostApiOrigin}}` must accept browser requests from
the storefront origin `{{hostPageOrigin}}`. Headers the widget sends:
`Authorization`, `Content-Type`. Action-manifest verbs:
`GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE`.

Required response headers:

- `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: {{hostPageOrigin}}`
- `Access-Control-Allow-Methods: GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE, OPTIONS`
- `Access-Control-Allow-Headers: Authorization, Content-Type`
{{#if (eq authMode "cookie")}}- `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true` *(required for cookie mode)*
{{/if}}

If your host API is also a Next.js app, drop this `middleware.ts` at the
project root:

```ts
import { NextResponse, type NextRequest } from "next/server";

export function middleware(req: NextRequest) {
  const res = NextResponse.next();
  res.headers.set("Access-Control-Allow-Origin", "{{hostPageOrigin}}");
  res.headers.set(
    "Access-Control-Allow-Methods",
    "GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE, OPTIONS",
  );
  res.headers.set(
    "Access-Control-Allow-Headers",
    "Authorization, Content-Type",
  );
{{#if (eq authMode "cookie")}}  res.headers.set("Access-Control-Allow-Credentials", "true");
{{/if}}  if (req.method === "OPTIONS") return new Response(null, { status: 204, headers: res.headers });
  return res;
}

export const config = { matcher: "/api/:path*" };
```

For Express / Fastify / etc. behind Next.js, use the standard `cors`
middleware with the same origin/methods/headers values.

## 4. Run the ATW backend

The emitted `atw/.env.example` already inlines `DATABASE_URL` and
`ALLOWED_ORIGINS` from `project.md`. Paste your `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`
and start the container.

**bash**

```bash
cp atw/.env.example atw/.env
# edit atw/.env and set ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...
docker run --rm \
  --env-file atw/.env \
  -p 4000:4000 \
  atw_backend:latest
```

**PowerShell**

```powershell
Copy-Item atw/.env.example atw/.env
# edit atw\.env and set ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...
docker run --rm `
  --env-file atw/.env `
  -p 4000:4000 `
  atw_backend:latest
```

The backend requires Postgres with the `pgvector` extension. The demo
`docker-compose.yml` wires this up; `DATABASE_URL` in
`atw/.env.example` already targets that container.

## 5. Static assets

Place `widget.js` and `widget.css` in your Next.js `public/` directory
(same folder as `favicon.ico`). Build-time-frozen containers must be
rebuilt before changes take effect.

